/*! @arch_page arch-disagg-cross-checkpoint-caching Cross-Checkpoint Caching

WiredTiger's cross-checkpoint caching feature reduces redundant network reads
and unnecessary memory usage on disaggregated standbys by sharing disk images
in memory across checkpoints. When a standby picks up a new checkpoint
(see @ref arch-checkpoint), pages that are unchanged from the previous
checkpoint can be served directly from memory instead of being re-fetched from
remote storage. This feature is only active on disaggregated standby nodes;
see @ref ccc_states for when it is enabled and disabled.

The shared disk cache is implemented as a connection-level hash table keyed on
the address cookie. Because different files can hash to the same bucket, lookup
finds the correct disk image by walking the bucket's linked list and matching on
file ID, address size, and address cookie. Each entry holds a single disk image
buffer shared across all in-memory pages that reference the same block.
Normally each page owns its disk image buffer privately, but with the
cross-checkpoint cache, the disk image is owned by the cache entry and pages
share it instead. When a page is read, WiredTiger first checks the shared disk
cache for an existing entry. On a miss, it reads the block from remote storage
and adds the disk image to the shared disk cache. When the last page
referencing an entry is discarded, the entry is removed and the buffer freed.

Pages sharing a disk image do not count those bytes toward connection-level
cache totals (\c bytes_inmem). The shared disk cache counts them once when
the entry is first inserted and drains them when the last reference is
released. Each page's \c memory_footprint still includes the disk image size
for per-page eviction decisions.

@section ccc_key_files Key files

| File | Role |
|------|------|
| \c src/include/cache.h | \c WT_SHARED_DSK_CACHE struct and state definitions |
| \c src/include/btmem.h | \c shared_dsk_item pointer in the page's \c WT_PAGE_DISAGG_INFO |
| \c src/btree/bt_read.c | call site: get on page fault-in, put after storage read |
| \c src/btree/bt_discard.c | call site: release when a page is discarded |
| \c src/cache/shared_dsk.c | get, put, release, init, and destroy |
| \c src/cache/cache.c | cache creation and destruction wiring |
| \c src/conn/conn_layered.c | step-up transition (ACTIVE to READONLY) and step-down transition (back to ACTIVE) |
| \c src/conn/conn_sweep.c | sweep server flipping READONLY to DEAD after the grace period |

@section ccc_lifecycle Lifecycle of the cache

The cache is created in \c __wt_cache_create when a disaggregated connection
opens on a standby, and it starts in \c WT_DSK_CACHE_ACTIVE. On connection
close, it is destroyed in \c __wt_cache_destroy. State transitions on step-up
and beyond are described in @ref ccc_states.

@section ccc_ops Cache Operation Implementations

- <b>get</b> (\c __wt_shared_dsk_cache_get): looks up an entry by file ID and
  address cookie. On a hit the reference count is incremented and the caller
  receives a pointer to the cached disk image. On a miss the caller reads from
  storage as usual.

- <b>put</b> (\c __wt_shared_dsk_cache_put): inserts a newly read disk image.
  If an entry for that address already exists its reference count is
  incremented and \c inserted is set to false; the caller must free the
  redundant buffer. On a fresh insert \c inserted is set to true and the cache
  takes ownership of the data.

- <b>release</b> (\c __wt_shared_dsk_cache_release): decrements the reference
  count. When the count reaches zero the entry is removed from the hash table
  and its buffer freed.

@section ccc_data_structures Data structures

Two structs in \c src/include/cache.h implement the cache.

\c WT_SHARED_DSK_CACHE is the top-level object, embedded in \c WT_CACHE:

- \c state: atomic \c uint8_t holding the current \c WT_DSK_CACHE_STATE
  (see @ref ccc_states).
- \c readonly_since: atomic wall-clock timestamp (seconds) recording when the
  cache transitioned to \c READONLY on step-up (see @ref ccc_lifecycle).
- \c hash / \c hash_size: bucket array sized at roughly 0.2% of configured
  cache, with a floor of 1000 buckets.
- \c hash_locks / \c hash_lock_size: spinlock array, striped across buckets
  so that each lock guards a group of buckets.

\c WT_SHARED_DSK_ITEM is a single cache entry:

- \c fid + \c addr[]: composite lookup key: file ID and address cookie.
- \c data / \c data_size: cached disk image buffer and its length.
- \c ref_count: number of in-memory pages sharing this entry; incremented on
  get or put collision, decremented on release. Drops to zero causes the entry
  to be immediately removed and the buffer freed. Protected by the bucket
  spinlock.
- \c block_meta: \c WT_PAGE_BLOCK_META copied into the page's \c disagg_info
  on a cache hit, avoiding a storage round-trip.

Each in-memory page that holds a reference stores a pointer to its
\c WT_SHARED_DSK_ITEM in \c page->disagg_info->shared_dsk_item
(see \c src/include/btmem.h).

@section ccc_states State machine

Cross-checkpoint caching is only enabled on disaggregated standbys, because
leader reads come from the live btree rather than older checkpoint images.
The cache moves through the following states over the lifetime of a connection:

| State | Who enters it | Reads allowed | Writes (puts) allowed |
|-------|--------------|---------------|-----------------------|
| \c WT_DSK_CACHE_OFF | Leader that has never been a standby; non-disagg connections | No | No |
| \c WT_DSK_CACHE_ACTIVE | Standby | Yes | Yes |
| \c WT_DSK_CACHE_READONLY | Immediately after step-up to leader | Yes | No |
| \c WT_DSK_CACHE_DEAD | After the sweep server's grace period elapses on a leader | No | No |

On step-up, the cache moves from \c ACTIVE to \c READONLY so that warm pages
already in the cache continue to be served. A grace period
(\c WT_DISAGG_OUTDATED_GRACE_SECS) controls how long the cache remains in
\c READONLY: once the reuse window expires, the sweep server flips it to
\c DEAD. The sweep server preserves outdated stable-checkpoint dhandles for
that grace period instead of discarding them immediately, allowing the next
checkpoint generation to reuse the shared disk image.

On step-down, the cache transitions back to \c ACTIVE. If the hash table was
never initialized (i.e. the node started as a leader and was not previously a standby),
it is created at this point, otherwise the existing table is reused.

*/
